title: How bystanders can perform high quality CPR, using the TCPR link
How high quality CPR can drastically increase the chance of survival from cardiac arrest
New Component Title
body: Created by Laerdal Medical 2020

title: The importance of CPR
body:
The odds of surviving from sudden out-of-hospital cardiac arrest is only about 10 percent.

However, if high quality CPR is delivered immidiately after cardiac arrest the chances of survival increases to 45 percent.
 

https://cpr.heart.org/en/resources/cpr-facts-and-stats

title: New Component Title
body:
TCPR link connects bystanders of cardiac arrest with emergency telephone operators.

By transmitting live data of the CPR performance from the bystander, the dispatcher is able to provide critical telephone support, to optimize quality of CPR delivered before the ambulance personnel arrives and takes over.

title: A card and an app
body:
TCPR link is comprised of a CPR Card and a Smartphone App. 

The CPR card is connected to your smartphone. It should be placed on the chest of the patient to measure the rate and depth of your compressions and provide continuous visual feedback.

The smartphone app also provides visual feedback and streams your performance data in real time to the dispatcher, who is a skilled CPR coach that will guide and encourage you to perform quality CPR until the ambulance arrives and takes over.

title: Step 3/7: Turn on CPR Card
body:
Press the power button to turn on the CPR card.

It will now automatically connect to your phone through Bluetooth.

title: Step 5/7: Phone placement
body:
Place your phone face-up beside the patient's head and kneel down by the patient's shoulder opposite your phone and prepare to give CPR.

title: Step 7/7: Begin CPR
body:
You are now ready to begin giving chest compressions.

You will receive continuous visual feedback on both your compression depth and rate on the screen of your phone.

title: CPR feedback indicators
body:
< Simon, can you make sure the illustrations are aligned with the text?
Also, can you remove the text to the furtherst right? - Correct depth and rate etc....
Make a new page for TCPRLink feedback description following the principle as the card:
- Correct depth and rate
- Too shallow and too fast
- Too deep and too slow

Correct depth and rate

The green light in the rate indicator lights up when a rate of 100 - 120 compressions per minute is reached.

Compression target for patient on a firm surface.  A steady green light will light up when you reach the target.

 

Too shallow and too fast

A steady yellow light will light up in the arrow or first bar if compressions are too shallow. Press deeper to achieve your depth target.

The left light in the rate indicator lights up yellow if the compression rate is too low

 

Too deep and too slow

A steady yellow light will light up in the arrow or third bar if compressions are too deep. Release pressure to achieve your depth target.

The right light in the rate indicator lights up yellow if the compression rate is too high.

title: How to use CPRcard
body:
Turn the CPRcard on by pinching and holding the On/Off button. Two yellow lights will start flashing indicating that the device is on and ready for use. 

Take off the liner only when using the CPRcard on a patient. Place the card with the placement line in the center of the chest. The feedback panel shall face towards the head of the patient. If needed wipe fluids off the chest.

Do not remove the liner if you only practice CPR with CPRcard on a manikin. 

Use standard CPR hand placement technique. When the hands are placed correctly on the CPRcard, the feedback panel should be visible.

body:
1. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

describe the importance of quality CPR in the case of cardiac arrest,  

by indicating how high quality CPR improves the chance of survival.  

2. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

list the components of quality CPR, (e.g. banner notifications of what’s quality CPR, at regular intervals)

by correctly identifying all the components (/minimum 80% of the components)

 

4. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

recall the importance of placing the patient on the floor before CPR,

by selecting the correct statements about how patient placement influences CPR quality.

 

6. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

recall the purpose of the CPR card,

by selecting all the correct statements about the functions of the CPR card. (/minimum 80% of the functions)

7. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

recall the purpose of the TCPR Link App

by selecting all the correct statements about the functions of the CPR card. (/minimum 80% of the functions)

 

9. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

recall the meaning of the feedback indicators on the CPR card

by matching the feedback indicators with the correct statements.

10. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

recall the meaning of the feedback indicators from the TCPR Link App

by matching the feedback indicators with the correct statements.

11. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

recall the dispatcher’s role of monitoring live data from TCPR link

by selecting the correct statement

12. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

recall the dispatcher’s role of coaching the MyResponder during a cardiac arrest incident

by matching examples of coaching to the role of the dispatcher.    

13. Upon completion of this e-learning course

the MyResponder is able to

Infer the meaning of the instructions from the dispatcher

by correctly matching minimum 80% the examples of actual dispatcher instructions to their paraphrased versions.
